before_you_start.browser_title = Before you start
before_you_start.title = Calculate what Residential Nil Rate Band (RNRB) is available for an estate
before_you_start.guidance1 = You can claim an allowance for either:
before_you_start.guidance1.bullet1 = a property in the deceased’s estate
before_you_start.guidance1.bullet2 = a property that was sold or downsized by the deceased
before_you_start.guidance2 = You may be able to add on an additional allowance if:
before_you_start.guidance2.bullet1 = the deceased had a spouse or civil partner who died before them
before_you_start.sub_heading = Before you start
before_you_start.guidance3 = You’ll need the following information to get an accurate figure using the calculator.
before_you_start.guidance4 = Claim an allowance for a property in the deceased’s estate
before_you_start.guidance4.bullet1 = When the deceased died - if they died before 6 April 2017 then you won’t be able to claim this allowance
before_you_start.guidance4.bullet2 = If the estate includes a property that the deceased owned and was their home, and/or the deceased owned a property that was their home - if not then you won’t be able to claim this allowance
before_you_start.guidance4.bullet3 = If any part of the property is being left to direct descendents - if not you won’t be able to claim this allowance
before_you_start.guidance4.bullet4 = The value of the assets in the estate - if it was over £2 million you won’t be able to claim the full allowance. You’ll calculate this using the IHT-700 form
before_you_start.guidance4.bullet5 = What exemptions and debts are in the estate. You’ll calculate this using IHT-700
before_you_start.guidance4.bullet6 = The open market value of the property at date of death, minus any mortgages
before_you_start.guidance4.bullet7 = If the property is also eligible for any form of inheritance tax exemption or tax relief, and if so how much. You’ll get this from the s.38IHTA or s.39IHTA grossing up calculator
before_you_start.guidance5 = If the estate is eligible for this allowance, you’ll need to put this figure on the IHT-435 form and the grossing-up calculators.
before_you_start.guidance6 = Claim the allowance for a property that was sold or downsized
before_you_start.guidance6.bullet1 = If any parts of the estate are being inherited by a direct descendent - if there is nothing you won’t be able to claim this allowance
before_you_start.guidance6.bullet2 = If the property was the deceased’s home that they owned and disposed of in their lifetime - if this doesn’t apply you won’t be able to claim this allowance
before_you_start.guidance6.bullet3 = When it was sold or downsized - if it was before 8 July 2015 then you won’t be able to claim this allowance.
before_you_start.guidance6.bullet4 = The value of the property when it was sold (or open market value on the date it was given away), minus any mortgages
before_you_start.guidance6.bullet5 = The value of the assets being inherited by direct descendents (you’ll get this from the s.38IHTA or s.39IHTA grossing up calculator)
before_you_start.guidance7 = If the estate is eligible for this allowance, you’ll need to add this figure to the IHT-435 form.
before_you_start.guidance8 = If the deceased had a spouse or civil partner who died before them and you want to add on their allowance
before_you_start.guidance8.bullet1 = When the spouse or civil partner died - if you’re claiming downsizing allowance only and they died on or before 5 April 2017 you won’t be able to use this allowance
before_you_start.guidance8.bullet2 = The value of the estate when they died without including inheritance tax exemptions or reliefs - if it was over £2 million you won’t be able to claim the full allowance. You’ll get this from either their IHT-205 or IHT-400 form.
before_you_start.guidance9 = If the estate is eligible for this allowance, you’ll need to also fill out the IHT-436 form.

